CSS section:Sets the initial display of #menustate to none, hiding it.
Defines styling for the hamburger button (label element).
Attempts to hide the navigation menu and close button using display: none.
Uses :is() pseudo-class to select either ul or .close elements within nav.
Selects .open within nav to hide the open button.
Defines styling for li elements to be displayed inline-flex.

HTML section:Creates a label for menustate with open and close spans inside.
Lists navigation items within a <ul> element.
Each navigation item is wrapped in an <li> element containing a button.
An image is included within one of the list items, although its positioning may need adjustment.
 








#menustate {
   display: none;
 }
 
 label {
   /* Basic styling of hamburger button */
   display: grid;
   place-content: center;
   width: 2.5rem;
   height: 2.5rem;
   font-size: 2rem;
   background: #ccf;
 }
 // good idea but, I cannot make a picture show up on the while running the server
 nav ul,
 nav .close {
   //Hide the menu and close button 
   display: none;
 }
 
 #menustate:checked ~ nav :is(ul, .close) {
   // Show the menu and close button 
   display: block;
 }
 
 #menustate:checked ~ nav .open {
   // Hide the open button 
   display: none
 }
 li {
     display:inline-flex;
 }

 <input aria-hidden="true" type="checkbox" id="menustate" />
 <label for="menustate" aria-hidden="true">
 <span class="open">≡</span>
 <span class="close">×</span>
         </label>
 <ul>
     <li><button>|Home|</button></li>
     <li><button>|Español|</button></li>
     <li><button>|Service|</button></li>
     <li><button>|Contact|</button></li>
     <li><button>|Reviews|</button></li>
  <li>
   <img style="position:absolute" src="https://latinospc.com/images/gallery/thumbnail/usbtypeA.jpg"></li>
 </ul> 